description.text:
Ever wanted to buy a spool of filament with a friend ? Ever wanted to split a full spool into two small ones ?
This thing will allow you to transfer as much as you want from one spool to another.
The needed bolt is calculated as to where a Wade's Hobbed Bolt is the perfect drop in replacement. If you have another length, this can easily be adjusted in the OpenScad-File.
As you can see on the pictures, it fits the two widely used spindel formats.
On one of the pictures, you can see that the hobbed bolt was clogged with some red filament grains when I started this build.
The circular teardrops are copied from some wade's.

Print it, drop in a M8x60, washer, nut, tighten, and then mount it on your power drill. The spools (source and destination) should both be spinning freely, either horizontally on two lazy suzy, or sitting on a peg on the wall.
You can easily derive a bearing / washer type of thing for center mounting.

title: Adjustable Limit Switch Cam Arm for Hex Shaft

description.text:
FRC Team 4026 needed an arm on a 1/2" hex shaft to trigger a limit switch (catapult design and we need to stop when it's cocked and then load the ball) so I replaced the ugly lexan hacked thing we used with this.
Two parts - there's the hub, which is designed to fit on the hex shaft and won't rotate and the cam arm, which has a round shaft hole and slots allowing for 90 degrees of adjustment off of the hex shaft alignment.  The two are attached with a pair of M3 bolts and captive nuts on the hub.
Make the cam diameter equal to the distance between your shaft and your limit switch and the bottom (there is a distinct "bottom" because that's the orientation we needed) of the cam should end up square to the switch when it hits.  The hub will be a little smaller than the cam.
There are a few places for fudge factors - I printed in ABS because that's what was on the printer, but it needs a little extra room for hole sizes.  PLA probably doesn't.  These include a 5% increase in nut size over "actual", .5mm for the shaft size.  Play with them as needed.
The cam has a scale on the edge to mark alignment and the hub a small bump to align to.  I added that after we made ours, so I can't promise anything other than they exist.
Warning - this was a really clean bit of openscad code to begin with and got a little messy as I added cute (though probably not necessary) features, like a scale around the edges of the cam, etc.  I'll clean it up when there's time, but wanted to put it out there in case any other FRC teams could make us of it.

title: Konami Eagle Landing Pad Display Stand

description.text:
Konami made several beautiful Space 1999 Eagle Replicas in the past several years. They measure just over 11cm in length and are just gorgeously detailed for their scale.  
This set of files prints a very nice display base for the Konami Eagle.  
It is based on the Landing Pad (for the tiny ERTL Eagles from the model kit) that I uploaded earlier. This was my original intent - to make this display base. The other diorama just happened by chance, happily.  
Print the Base, House and Extension in white. Print the Base_Black in black. Print the Base_Red in red. The two bases snap into place in the Base_White frame. NOTE: The pin holes are not aligned perfectly. They should allow for only ONE valid orientation.  
(I put a tiny notch in the upper left hole of the red base just so you can orient it correctly on the print bed, so that surface is facing up for a better surface finish.)  
There are two configurations of the smoke trails for the lift-off smoke - one flat, for an even lift-off display, and one tilted upward for a more dramatic lift-off. Choose whichever you wish.  
Photos here show both configurations.  
It is also possible the four individual smoke trails may be usable in other combinations I have not tried for a more gentle lift-off, or even by turning them around, a nose-down approach. You are free to play around.  
I did not model nice snap points. I'm afraid glue will have to be used to complete this model kit, and my favorite is clear binary epoxy cement. Krazy Glue works pretty well too.  
You must, sadly, supply your own Konami Eagle.

This was an alteration of my own model of an earlier upload, Thing #129700.  
This adds pegs to the base, holes to the two deck levels, which fit into smoke trails I modeled using the Sculpt tool in Maya to get a reasonable rocket trail.  
The idea is a forced-perspective view on a lift-off of a Moonbase Alpha Eagle. In reality the pad below would have to be about 15 inches in diameter, not including the housing extensions.  
I printed mine with the house, base and extension in a creamy white, while the rocket trails are a semi-translucent natural color, for a better smoke trail. Then the two deck pieces are in black and red.  The smoke trails may be nice in clear filament. I've never tried that one.  
Note: On an Afinia printer, a flat surface is printed on a diagonal. Because that didn't work well with the metal plating idea of the red cross landing platform, I rotated it 45 degrees so the printer printed on the correct axes for this piece.

The neck snaps into the body and the head. The arms, however, will need gluing. They shoulder ball sits in the socket, but not to hold. Gluing will be necessary. But the ball allows you to glue the arms at any angle you like. Note: The detail is low on this model, but it's a work in progress. Note 2: The upper arms and lower left and right arms are practically identical. You can probably just print two of the same upper and lower. That would work.

The level of detail is such that it is likely best to print the text/arrow buttons using Laser Sintering rather than Fused Filament Deposition.

Originally I just wanted colored buttons, so I measured the button dimensions and recreated them in Tinkercad. I added a little rim to the bottom of the blank button, and then lined up the 4 buttons with the original 4-button action pad STL (the X and Y spacing are not equal). Then I thought - what about letters? I embossed some letters, and ended up with the Unkeyed variant buttons. I then realized that even though they were intended to be a tight press fit, the buttons might rotate, and so I created the Keyed variants. Finally, I figured that while I was add it, I might as well dress up the D-Pad a bit. The sharp arrow variant was created first, but I realized that the sharp interior corners might not print well, so I created the soft variant as well. I ran everything though Microsoft's Model Repair Service - NetFabb cloud. And I uploaded everything here!

This is inspired by user delukat's adjustable feet for the Wanhao i3, link below:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:916707 I had some issues with the threads being loose when printed, as well as there not being enough interlocking thread when the 2 parts are screwed together. One of the photos shows my design and delukat's side by side. I printed all these at 100 micron resolution to get the best accuracy on the threads, but still just found them a little too loose. So I started from scratch, this design uses a M8x1.25 thread with 12mm on the clamp which attaches to the printer frame and 20mm thread on the foot. I made the foot with 12 sides and created a small spanner/wrench, which makes fine adjustments a bit easier as the foot base is only 6mm thick. The tolerances on the threads are quite tight, the foot base has an extra 100 microns breathing space and the frame clamp assembly has 100 microns as well. I made several trials with the frame clamp assembly and 50, 75 and 100 microns, 75 and 100 worked ok for me but 50 was a little too tight. The 100 microns gap on each part equates to 200 micron (0.2mm see images) gap overall, which should offer the best compromise to all, hopefully. **Added a 2nd frame clamp version, this is a low profile version and drops the frame clip an additional 3mm. A photo is attached showing all 3 versions side by side, it uses the same bolt assembly. You can use a standard M8 metal nut to hone the foot assembly thread if necessary.

description.text:
These are to replace the wooden bearing sleeves on the Y axis.
There is a new all aluminum bearing sleeve that PB sells as an upgrade for the LCv2, this is a cheap and nearly as good alternative. Print the file 4 times for a set of 2 bearing sleeves, the original fastener hardware can be re-used, but i recommend lock nuts and washers over the stock hardware. comments.text: Just a tip: when assembling, put the bearings on an 8mm rod first, then install in these sleeves. if the bearings end up too tight, try again until you get them aligned right. it likely wont be possible to put the bearings in these sleeves without being on the rod, for alignment, unless you are really lucky.
comments.author: plexus

comments.text:
hmm,. I installed the bearings without
rod just fine, the cavity for the bearings is (should be) slightly smaller than
the bearings themselves, so the act of closing the two clam shells together and
then compressing the two clam shells together via the screws should auto align
the bearings every time. But using the rod as added linear assurance during assembly cant hurt. i found having the bearings ball channels apposing (not lined up between the two) to be the most rigid and smooth glide. but if you are binding up, to get a little wiggle room line them up.
comments.author: plexus

comments.text: On my print the cavities are smaller than the bearings and required pressing in, in order to assemble. one thing to keep in mind is that every one's printer will have a slightly different calibration. also, different materials and ambient temperatures will result in different amounts of shinkage and warping. it a good idea when making a design public to accommodate for these differences.
comments.author: AlexCphoto

comments.text: Aye, this print does have a tight tolerance window, so variance from printer to printer could be problematic, but its an item to add stability/accuracy, frequently parts like that have to be spot on. And my thought on variance is that you make the model accurate, and you adjust your printer till its closer to accurate rather than me changing the model to factor for only one specific printers inaccuracy (in that case its still inaccurate for everyone else,. my printer is currently at ~+.04mm accuracy if your near that this should print right. (hydrated filament can also cause extra "balooning"). other option is openscad with a tolerance variable, but im an artist/engineer not a programmer, Open scad is like nails on a chalkboard to me.. but if enough folks request it I might give it a try.

For a thermodynamics class I decided to see if I could make a working water turbine. This is just a little thing I threw together to fit a spare 1.25" diameter DC motor I had laying around. I printed all the parts, which took about 6 hours (mostly due to the .1mm thick run I did for the turbine blade) and assembled them as shown. Due to some warping some parts needed sanding in order to fit together. Once everything was assembled, I fused the parts together with a soldering iron and extra plastic filament. Then I fused a 3/4 " tube to the top and added a water hose attachment.
it ended up powering a LED, generating about 5 volts with a water hose turned on half way (and generating about 10 volts by blowing into it) so it isn't that impressive.

title: LED strip holder clip for CTC/Flashforge/Makerbot Clone printer

description.text:
LED strip holder clip for CTC/Flashforge/Replicator/Makerbot clone printers I have bought some cheap 5050 SMD LED-strips from ebay http://www.ebay.de/itm/221926233341 (1,99€ for 4 pieces included shipping) and wanted to mount them on my CTC Printer. The tape on the stripes doesn't stick well on the wood frame of the printer. Normal double sided tape would have done the trick. But i decided to mount the stripes under a 40° angle to light the actual printbed. The original idea is from http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1194640. Thanks a lot. But i didn't want to wast so many filament for only a LED strip holder. And the 150mm or 300mm length are not so good to print on the CTC. The 5050 SMD LED strip from ebay is around 100mm long and waterproof sealed. This
makes it very stiff and perfect for a two point mounting. You can clip this on any side of the printer (see pictures)

2x of the mounting clips for one LED strip (http://www.ebay.de/itm/221926233341).
I've put some double sided tape under the top of the printer to fix the position. It's not needed because the clips fit well, but i waned to be extra safe.

The infll shouldn't have too much impact on this object, so I just used the default infill percentage of 20%. To make this object stronger, and less likely to break, just raise this to around 40%.

Notes: This should fit on most printer beds, considering I printed it with a Lulzbot Mini, but just in case, you should make sure that the build volume of your printer has a height large enough to fit this object. Note: Be sure to orient the cup in the right direction before printing. Leaving the cup on its side will not result in a very good print.

Main Obstacle The most difficult aspect of designing this for me was getting a 2D sketch on a 3D surface. In order to do this in Fusion 360, there first needs to be a sketch tangent to the surface you want to project onto, and then use the feature 'Project to Surface' to transfer the sketch onto the surface. Once this is completed, you then create construction planes along the new paths created along the 3D surface, and sketch a shape that will be used to cut out the surface onto the construction plane. Once this is done, using a 'Sweep' tool and sweeping this new construction sketch to cut out a shape along the 3D path allows the type of effect shown in the images. This was definitely time consuming and a challenge for me, but was well worth the effort to learn how to accomplish this.

Assembly Check fit of M3 holes, and ream/drill if necessary. Clean out trap nut holes (it prints without support, they just get a little ugly) and add trap nuts. If you have first layer mash you may need to use a vise or hammer to get them in. There are five of them. Add endstop to the appropriate part, threading screws directly into the plastic on the side with the ledge. If they don't fit well, change g2mm constant in scad and reprint. (I haven't had luck with using a small drill bit to enlarge.) Hand tighten M3x12 to trap nuts. For the lower part, the cut corner goes up, toward the endstop (this is obvious if you have the endstop attached). See photo on this step, you can use a little stack of washers to help it sit flat while you tighten. The curved corners of the top part halves go together, as in photo. Add spring and M3x40 to top part. Spring and screw head go opposite the nut. Clamps! The screws should go right against the metal edge. For the upper part, it's self-aligning at the corner as well. For the lower part, you may need to move it around until you find the right spot. Start with where the old holes are, and go down from there.
I used OpenSCAD 2015.03 and coded by hand. The adjuster screw position is similar to the one I was using before, http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:928008

Clathrate hydrate is a solid solution made of gas and water.  Methane hydrate is the most famous clathrate hydrate, but many other gases also form the clathrate hydrate.
Its crystal structure is quite complicated.  In clathrate hydrates, the gas molecules are contained in the cages made of water molecules.  There are three major type of cages, 12-, 14- and 16-hedra.  Methane hydrate consists of 12- and 14-hedra, whereas hydrogen hydrate is composed of 12- and 16-hedra.
The unit cell of the methane hydrate consists of 46 water molecules and 8 methane molecules.  They are extraordinarily large numbers; Unit cells of the face-centered cubic and body-centered cubic lattice only consists of 4 and 2 atoms, respectively.  The unit cell of hydrogen hydrate consists of 136 water molecules and 24 hydrogen molecules, and there are eight 16-hedral cages and sixteen 12-hedral cages in a single unit cell.
It is therefore very difficult to imagine the structure of these hydrates.  So, I made this puzzle.  This puzzle mimics the unit cell structure of the hydrogen hydrate.  In the photograph, blue and white parts corresponds to 16-hedral and 12-hedral cages.  Hydrogen molecules reside at the centers of these cages.
The inner dimension of the cubic acrylic box is 62.5 mm.  "x4" in the STL filename indicates the number of the part required make a unit cell.  The THING file includes all the required copies of the parts.
Enjoy!

description.text:

I am using Pololu 37D motors (https://www.pololu.com/product/2826). Due to the size and weight each bigger wheel need two 10x15x4 bearings, and each smaller wheel one 5x10x4 bearing. Motor-Wheel connection is realised by two M4 grub screws (Place for M4 Nuts is also provided). To connect Frame Parts you need M3 screws. Final dimensions of fully assembled platform:

title: HICTOP Essential prints - Prusa I3 Kit

description.text:
This is a collection of parts that I believe are essential for the best operation of the HICTOP Reprap Prusa I3 3D printer (kit). Hopefully someone else will get some helpful use out of these as well. Layer height at .3mm is totally fine for all of these parts, which will save you a lot of print time. 1) Spool Holder Tube:
The supplied spool holder doesn't work well because the center of gravity is off. I've designed this tube to integrate with the supplied spool holder. Simply print this tube, slide it onto the threaded rod and tighten nuts around it. Put this inside your spool's hole, and then place it onto the supplied mount. It will roll MUCH MUCH easier on the spool now. This is designed to fit most 2.2lbs (1kg) spools. I print this particular part at 10% infill to save print time, and its strong enough. Feel free to increase the infill to your liking. 2) Filament runner:
To go with #1. This runner slides firmly onto the TOP of your acrylic frame, so the hole is facing towards the front/back of the printer. Place your spool holder behind your print bed, feed the filament through this runner's hole, and then down into your extruder. This will allow smooth, yet contained, movement of the filament and it will feed to the printer perfectly when paired with #1 above. I print this at 20% infill. It's small and doesn't take long to print. 3) Switch holder:
For some reason, the power supply does not have a main power switch. Use this bracket to fit a generic medium size rocker switch. Ideal for mounting on the right side frame, where it sits in-between the power supply and the frame. A dab of super glue to the acrylic frame will hold it in place and still allow you to remove the power supply if ever needed. Then wire the switch in line with your AC input, and now you have a handy way to turn the unit off and on. I print this part at 20% infill, its really strong. 4) Cable Holder:
This mounts to the top part of the frame and uses the included frame bolts to hold it to the frame. Use this clamp to hold your wires that go to your X movement. It will keep them nice and secure while allowing smooth, unrestricted movement to every part of the bed, without snagging or dragging on anything. I print at 20% infill.

This project is made to be a visual representation of the plot line. Some students have a hard time understanding the way plot works so this will help those students see the exposition, rising action, climax, falling action, then finally the conclusion.
Parts Included : The car of the rollercoaster, the start/finish (they are the same), and the middle.
Also we printed a small car to show the movement of a story in a book. To show the parts of plot on the rollercoaster, the teacher can create notes or paper to put on the spot where needed.

Step 1 First we saw that the problem given to us was to make a object, only using the 3-d printer, that could help a teacher on a subject. Step 2 We first thought up of multiple ideas and one of them included a rollercoaster to explain plot another one was to make shapes. Step 3 We did some research on all our ideas and saw that the rollercoaster would be pretty simple but would help enough. Step 4 We knew we can only have it 3-d printed, it must be educational, and must be able to be used by a teacher to teach a lesson. Step 5 After looking back at our ideas we got rid of the shapes due to it not really being of use and a few other small ideas. Step 6 We chose the rollercoaster that taught plot due to the complexity of plot as a lesson and how students have a hard time learning it. Step 7 We then developed a design proposal about the rollercoaster. Step 8 We then created the rollercoaster and car in inventor.

Objectives The objective is to make it easier for students to learn about plot. Audiences Students in 7th grade MC2 who are not the best at ELA. Preparation The only thing that is needed is for the teacher to have post it notes on the roller coaster to label the parts. Results Students should have seen a visual representation of the plot line.

You must read the "post-printing", maybe will be IMPORTANT to you. And don't forget click Like/Made if this has been useful to you ;) Note: be carefull with the light's heat. Especially if you use PLA, if the lamp is to near of lithophane, it will deformed it. I recomend LED or 9W max. Update 7/06/17: I have upload a new lower panel version to adapt a G9 lights. They are the best lights to this lamp so if you want one, I recommend to you this new version. UPDATE 22/11/17: re-design the corners and boths Lower Panels to improve some problems with resistence of the corners. They have now wider walls. IN ADITTION: you must put when you created the lithophane around 2.98mm thickness because of sometimes, like Slic3r, make the litho with +0.2-0.3 mm higher, so with 3.3mm thickness you will have problems to assembly.
